title: For Sale/Trade:  Stevens 14 1/2 Little Scout
postcontent:
Time for this one to find a new home. Neat old gun and fun to shoot, but it doesn't fit in my collection anymore.

This gun is from before the Savage buyout of Stevens in 1920. No serial number or date, other than the patent date of 7/2/1907. 

The finish is lacking, but this is a 100 year old rifle. It's been used, obviously, but no damage. The stock is as good as I've seen one one. The buttplate appears original, not the flatter styles you see on some. I'm sure the bore has some wear, but plenty of rifling intact and it's in good shape.

I've shot this gun on several occasions without issue. As a disclaimer, if you are not familiar with these older falling blocks do NOT shoot high velocity ammunition out of it. I'd recommend care shooting even standard velocity. I've shot Federal AutoMatch out of it without any issues, but some others have resulted in bulging cases or backing out of the breach block.

I can send more pictures upon request.

I have a C&R FFL, so I will need a bill of sale with appropriate information for my bound book. I am open to shipping to a C&R or FFL on your dime (actual shipping cost). Open to offers if you think price is high. Worst I can say is no thank you.

This scope features resettable 1/10 milliradian (MIL) windage and elevation turrets and a Mil-dot reticle, this is also known as MIL/MIL. The combination of these two features enables the shooter to make quick and precise corrections. By using the Mil-dot reticle to measure how far off the shot is in MILs, each dot is 1 MIL apart, the shooter does not need to convert milliradians to minutes of angle in order to correct the point of aim. With traditional 1/4 MOA turrets, if the point of impact is measured to be 1.5 mils low the shooter needs to convert the Mils to MOA and then adjust the turrets which can be confusing. With a Mil/Mil rifle scope if the shot is 1.5 mils low then the shooter simply turns the turret 1.5 mils or 15 clicks. The mil-dot reticle can also be used to determine how far away an object of known size is. title: For Sale/Trade:  Stevens Little Scout 14 1/2
postcontent:
Time for this one to find a new home. Neat old gun and fun to shoot, but it doesn't fit in my collection anymore.

This gun is from before the Savage buyout of Stevens in 1920. No serial number or date, other than the patent date of 7/2/1907. 

The finish is lacking, but this is a 100 year old rifle. It's been used, obviously, but no damage. The stock is as good as I've seen one one. The buttplate appears original, not the flatter styles you see on some. I'm sure the bore has some wear, but plenty of rifling intact and it's in good shape.

I've shot this gun on several occasions without issue. As a disclaimer, if you are not familiar with these older falling blocks do NOT shoot high velocity ammunition out of it. I'd recommend care shooting even standard velocity. I've shot Federal AutoMatch out of it without any issues, but some others have resulted in bulging cases or backing out of the breach block.

I can send more pictures upon request.

I have a C&R FFL, so I will need a bill of sale with appropriate information for my bound book. I am open to shipping to a C&R or FFL on your dime (actual shipping cost). Open to offers if you think price is high. Worst I can say is no thank you.

PSA lower receiver:
These lowers are made using the most advanced aerospace manufacturing technology to produce the industries finest, forged Mil-Spec lowers. Our receivers are machined on a multimillion dollar, automated, manufacturing system which enables us to produce a product of unequaled quality and value. 

These forged lowers are quality made using material is 7075-T6 and are marked "CAL MULTI" to accommodate most builds.  Finish is Black Hardcoat Anodize per MIL-8625 Type 3 class 2.


Vltor A5 reduced recoil buffer system:
The A5 Combo Kit features a longer receiver extension, longer housing, a specially weighted buffer and includes the M16A2 buffer spring. The smoother function and constant spring rate of the M16A2 buffer spring increases accuracy, reliability and performance. The A5 Combo Kit is an excellent choice for addition to any AR platform but is a notably superb upgrade for piston systems. Many piston systems suffer from over-gassed operation and excessive carrier velocities which, both of which can lead to an unreliable firearm and a decrease in accuracy. The A5 system has been proven to tame such problematic tendencies and often increases the reliability and accuracy of the weapon. 

The A5 Modstock (EMOD) features a wider and longer butt with strike plate, removable and waterproof side compartments with storage for four CR123 or three AA batteries and another weatherproof compartment on the clubfoot that holds two AA batteries or other small items. The A5 kit includes the EMOD stock, battery compartments and butt/strike plate, an A5 seven-position receiver extension buffer tube, A5 mid-length 5.3oz buffer (standard weight), M16A2/A5 buffer spring, receiver extension buffer tube end plate and a receiver extension buffer tube lock ring. 

Technical Information: 
Design
Specially developed buffer and receiver extension, which works with the known M16A2 action spring. This combination of components helps increase the reliability and lowers rate of fire for all AR-15 type firearms.

Construction 
Impact and temperature resistant polymer, specially blended for Vltor. Metal components are either carbon steel or stainless steel (depending on the application)

Compatibility
Compatible with most AR15 platforms: Direct gas-impingement and Piston-driven. The current A5 system is NOT compatible with .308 caliber AR platforms.

•Length of pull (fully extended): 12.50 inches
